        "description": {
            "name": "description",
            "type": "java.lang.String",
            "value": "The following test fails:\r\n\r\n{code:none}\r\n$docSrc = \r\n    '<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\" ?>\r\n    <html xmlns=\"http:\/\/www.w3.org\/1999\/xhtml\">\r\n    <head><title \/><\/head>\r\n    <body><p>Test paragraph.<\/p><\/body>\r\n    <\/html>';\r\n\r\n$domDoc = new DOMDocument();\r\n$domDoc->loadXML($docSrc);\r\n$xpath  = new DOMXPath($domDoc);\r\n$nodeList = $xpath->query('\/\/p');\r\n$this->assertTrue($nodeList->length == 1);\r\n{code}\r\n\r\nThe workaround I found is:\r\n{code:none}\r\n$domDoc = new DOMDocument();\r\n$domDoc->loadXML($docSrc);\r\n$xpath  = new DOMXPath($domDoc);{code}\r\n*{code:none}\r\n$xpath->registerNamespace('xhtml', 'http:\/\/www.w3.org\/1999\/xhtml');\r\n$nodeList = $xpath->query('\/\/xhtml:p');\r\n{code}*\r\n{code:none}\r\n$this->assertTrue($nodeList->length == 1);\r\n{code}\r\n\r\nWhat that means for Zend? Nothing, it's a PHP bug,\r\n*BUT*\r\nassertXpath methods in the Zend Test suite, does nothing\r\nto enforce that workaround,\r\n*SO*\r\nassertXpath methods are incapable of treating XHTML documents.\r\n\r\nA workaround is:\r\n\r\n*{code:none}\r\n$this->dispatch('\/');\r\n$this->registerXpathNamespaces(array('xhtml' => 'http:\/\/www.w3.org\/1999\/xhtml'));\r\n$this->assertXpath('\/\/xhtml:p');\r\n{code}*\r\n\r\nA solution could be to improve the document type recognition by postponing this fragment\r\n{code:none}\r\nif ('<' . '?xml' == substr(trim($document), 0, 5)) {\r\n    return $this->setDocumentXml($document, $encoding);\r\n}\r\n{code}\r\n\r\nto this fragment\r\n\r\n{code:none}\r\nif (strstr($document, 'DTD XHTML')) {\r\n    return $this->setDocumentXhtml($document, $encoding);\r\n}\r\n{code}\r\n\r\n*SINCE*\r\nby W3C definition an XHTML document IS an XML document, the above solution is really a workaround for the uppermost PHP bug.\r\n\r\n*NOTE*\r\nI guess the order was chosen to improve the performance since strstr on a $document could be potentially slow, but I think that for real world cases this doesn't matter."
        },
